column30:
I also added an ask to prioritize K-12 public schools in the grants in HB 1012 with the following rationale: 

• Specifically, public schools are centrally located in communities across our state. Many are already designated FEMA sites. They generally have large gathering spaces and facilities to accommodate shelter and food preparation/storage. Supporting their use as community resilience hubs with ground-source heat pumps (for year-round heating and cooling), weatherization upgrades, off-grid solar energy, and/or V2G battery backup, etc, would also allow them to potentially utilize significant Direct Pay funding from the Inflation Reduction Act, make progress on their state building performance standards requirements (minimizing future climate impacts), significantly reduce operating costs, and improve student health and outcomes all-in-one!

column39: I hope you are tracking HB 2301. It passed the House, and is in Senate Committee.  It would decrease Food Waste and Improve Food Access: Addresses food and yard waste composting--especially important in much of the smaller cities and rural areas of the state that do no have this yet..
